Vectors: practice I

Lizzie Kumar

Building vectors

  1. Build the following vectors using the colon operator: :.

\[ \{-1, 0, 1, 2\} \\ \{2, 1, 0, -1\} \]

(-1):2
## [1] -1  0  1  2
-((-2):1)
## [1]  2  1  0 -1
  1. Build the following vectors using seq().

\[ \{-1, 0, 1, 2\} \\ \{2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12\} \\ \{2, 3.5, 5, 6.5\} \]

seq(-1, 2)
## [1] -1  0  1  2
seq(2, 12, 2)
## [1]  2  4  6  8 10 12
seq(2, 6.5, 1.5)
## [1] 2.0 3.5 5.0 6.5
  1. Build the following vectors using rep().

\[ \{1, 2, 3, 1, 2, 3, 1, 2, 3\} \\ \{1, 1, 2, 2, 3, 3\} \\ \{1, 1, 2, 3, 3\} \\ \{1, 2, 3, 1, 2, 3, 1\} \\ \{1, 1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 1, 1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 1, 1, 2, 2, 3, 3\} \]

rep(c(1,2,3), 3)
## [1] 1 2 3 1 2 3 1 2 3
rep()
## NULL

Manipulating vectors

Please paste the following commands into your Rstudio session, in order to set up the following exercises.

require('ggplot2')
load(url('http://www.stolaf.edu/people/olaf/cs125/hw8.RData'))

If at some point you want to restore the data, it is fine to paste these commands in again whenever you need them.

Let’s see whether the drawing function is working correctly. Try typing in the following command, and see what it does:

draw(p0x, p0y)

If all goes well, a simple sketch of Calvin should appear. If you print p0x, you will see that it is a vector of numbers, and p0y is another vector of numbers, both of the same length. p0x and p0y contain the x and y coordinates, respectively, of the points along the line segments that make up the simple Calvin sketch. As an experiment, try the following:

draw(p0x, p0y+25)

Hopefully, the result is that Calvin appeared to move up a distance of 25 units. Before proceeding with the exercises, please think through what is happening with these commands, since it will be easier to answer the following questions if you clearly understand how the two vectors are related to the plot.

  1. If you now draw the next set of vectors:
draw(p1x, p1y)

you will see Calvin’s buddy Hobbes, except that there is a problem with the data: the points that are part of Hobbes on the right side have been mistakenly moved up by 25 units. Please fix this problem, so that drawing p1x with p1y results in a more plausible rendering of Hobbes.

  1. Let’s take a look at the second example:
draw(p2x, p2y)

here, we almost have four duplicates of Calvin in several places, but the upper right drawing has been shifted to the left. Please move that part of the drawing to the right, so that the four Calvins are symmetrically placed (the same distance apart both horizontally and vertically).

  1. Let’s take a look at the third example:
draw(p3x, p3y)

here, we almost have four duplicates of Hobbes in several places, but every other point has been moved five units up and to the right, making it almost impossible to see Hobbes anywhere. Try to resolve the four duplicates of Hobbes.
